{
  "doc_id": "10866",
  "text": "Site mutagenesis of NLS showed that the aNLS, rather than the bNLS, is essential for NS5 nuclear accumulation and viral replication, particularly as the mutation of 387 KKK 389 in DENV-2 NS5 abolished NS5 nuclear import and viral production, which suggested the integral role of nuclear NS5 during flavivirus infection [CITATION_1] . In ZIKV, the 390 KRPR 393 in the monopartite NLS is necessary to direct NS5 to the nucleus, and its mutation to 390 ARPA 393 changed NS5 localization from the nucleus to the cytoplasm [CITATION_2] . In addition, the C-terminal 18 amino acids of NS5 regulate the translocation of NS5 between the cytoplasm and nucleus. The P884T mutation resulted in the mislocalization of NS5 to the cytoplasm without compromising viral fitness, and the R888K mutation led to a severely attenuated phenotype, even though NS5 was located in the nucleus [CITATION_3] . Although a large proportion of NS5 accumulates in the nuclei of infected cells, the role of NS5 in the nucleus has not yet been elucidated. Recent studies have suggested that nuclear NS5 modulates host cell immune responses and virus production [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and affects the splicing of antiviral response mRNAs [CITATION_7] . In infected cells, NS5 is able to bind and degrade the IFN-regulated human transcriptional activator STAT2 to suppress type I interferon signaling in ZIKV [CITATION_8] . STAT1 is found to colocalized with ZIKV NS5, and overexpressed NS5 is able to upregulate STAT1 related genes, however, this regulation is dampened in response to expression of mislocated NS5 mutant [CITATION_9] .While in DENV, only proteolytically processed NS5 can efficiently mediate STAT2 degradation, particularly when the cellular protein UBR4 binds to NS5, while the unprocessed and processed forms of NS5 can bind NS5 [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Furthermore, nuclear NS5 is also thought to dampen the IL-8 induction response, resulting in increased virus production [CITATION_12] . Proteomic and transcriptome analyses of DENV-infected cells showed that nuclear NS5 interacts with the spliceosome U5 snRNP proteins and hijacks the splicing machinery, thus forming an environment less restrictive for viral replication [CITATION_13] . Analysis of the crystal structure of DENV NS5 showed that these two NLSs are present in the RdRp domain, raising the possibility that the NLS regulates RdRp activity via the rearrangement of NS5 [CITATION_14] .",
